	<item>
		<title>NGOCC condemns police brutality on Mutinta</title>
		<link>https://staging.themastonline.com/2017/02/22/ngocc-condemns-police-brutality-on-mutinta/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 22 Feb 2017 09:44:22 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[mast-admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://staging.themastonline.com/?p=9</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[NGOCC board chairperson Sarah Longwe says it was wrong for male police officers to harass Dr Fred M’membe’s wife Mutinta in the absence of her husband.

Commenting on police brutality on Mutinta who was arrested last Wednesday for questioning their presence at her home, Longwe stated that it was sad that police brutality against women was continuing.

“It is very sad indeed that police brutality is continuing against women as lately witnessed in the case of Mutinta Mazoka (M’membe), who was allegedly roughed up by police as they arrested her at her home. Why didn’t the police ensure that her husband, Mr. Fred M’membe, was in the house before going to the house with an arrest warrant for him because it is supposed to have been served on Mr M’membe and not the wife Mrs Mutinta M’membe? This is an affront to the human rights of Mrs M’membe. It is not a crime for one to be a wife to a man to be arrested by police nor for one to be found in the house without one’s husband whom the police want to arrest,” Longwe stated.

She urged the police to find better ways of arresting accused persons.

“Surely, there must be an amicable police routine for arresting accused persons without harassing any of their family members and it is sad because it is a legal requirement for police to grant police bond if requested by the accused as long as they meet the conditions. This is a further violation of Mrs M’membe’s human rights,” stated Longwe.]]></content:encoded>
