	<item>
		<title>Every dog has its day, GBM tells Lungu</title>
		<link>https://staging.themastonline.com/2017/02/22/every-dog-has-its-day-gbm-tells-lungu/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 22 Feb 2017 09:49:07 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[mast-admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://staging.themastonline.com/?p=19</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[&nbsp;

I AM not happy with what Edgar Lungu is doing to the press but he must know that every dog has its day, says Geoffrey Bwalya Mwamba.

The opposition UPND vice-president, who was among several notable figures that offered solidarity to Mutinta Mazoka M’membe when she appeared at Lusaka Magistrates’ Court on Monday, said he was disgusted by the continued muzzling of the press by the PF government.

Armed police officers last week raided journalist Dr Fred M’membe’s house on Lusaka’s Nangwenya Road and later arrested Mutinta for questioning the warrant.
<blockquote>After two days in incarceration, Mutinta appeared in court and was released on K3,000 bail.</blockquote>
“The media are being harassed left, right and centre by Edgar Lungu and his so-called government. Edgar thinks he will be there forever. Go and tell him that politics has a lifespan, the presidency has a lifespan; it is short-lived,” GBM said.

"What he is doing to us today, to the media will happen to him tomorrow. The country is watching.
<blockquote>I am not happy as a citizen of this country with what Edgar is doing to the press and individuals like Fred M’membe, even to an extent of harassing an innocent wife. What he is doing is nonsense and total rubbish. Go and tell him that GBM says every dog has its day.</blockquote>
He said it was unfortunate that President Lungu and the PF government’s ill reasoning on the closure of The Post sent over 1,300 workers on the street.

“How many people have lost their jobs through the closure of The Post? Over a thousand, and Lungu and his so-called government don’t even care! They think that they are punishing Fred M’membe but on the contrary, it’s the one thousand people and their families that they are punishing. They are now jobless. Why didn’t Edgar create employment for all those that he sent to the street after closing The Post?” asked GBM.

“Suppression of the press has never worked in any country. It only works for a short while but in the long run, it will boomerang. Not too long from now, the same media - Times of Zambia, Daily Mail and ZNBC - that he uses for his personal gains will be writing against Edgar Lungu. What goes around comes around.”

And Sylvia Masebo has asked first lady Esther Lungu to advise her husband to stop the current madness of brutality and attacks on independent media.

“I wish his wife (Esther Lungu) can advise him (President Lungu) because women normally, we are able to see beyond what our men see that this way of running our country is not the right way to run, this is madness and it is unacceptable and they can do whatever they want to do to us, but the time is going to come and when that time comes, they will not like it,” Masebo said.

Masebo said whereas President Lungu could today rejoice over his “unacceptable” conduct, his time would come.

"And when that time comes, he will not like it,” Masebo said when she visited Mutinta on Monday afternoon.

She reminded President Lungu that the same police officers he was abusing would pounce on him when ejected from power.

“Edgar is creating enemies for nothing and it’s a pity; I feel so sorry for him because this Constitution, I am sure he was hoping he was going to have a third term, but clearly he won’t have a third term and one year has already gone; he is remaining with four years,” Masebo said.

"Four years for some of us who have been in politics long enough and know, four - five years will finish only tomorrow, by the time he wakes up, he will no longer be in State House, those guys that are around him who are misleading him, they would have changed house by then, I feel sorry for him.”

She President Lungu’s regime was being brutal towards independent media in order to hide the crimes they were committing.

“For me, if you have noticed, I do not talk anymore because I told the Zambian people, you are making a mistake to put Lungu there, and look at what has happened to Zambia! The country is finished, we have no press freedom, we have nothing, it is just poverty and a few people who are stealing and abusing their positions and amassing wealth in the last 12 months,” said Masebo.]]></content:encoded>
